## `event-handlers/` — Domain Event Handlers (side effects)

React to domain events published via `EventBus`. Each handler is responsible for **one side effect** triggered by one event. Side effects include: sending notifications, updating projections, triggering downstream workflows.

**Rules:**
- Use `@EventsHandler(SomeDomainEvent)` from `@nestjs/cqrs` — required for `EventBus` routing.
- `@Injectable()` — NestJS DI is allowed.
- One handler file per event → one side effect. Do not pile multiple unrelated reactions into one handler class.
- Never mutate domain state inside an event handler — if mutation is needed, dispatch a new command via `CommandBus`.
- Never import Prisma types or call `prisma.*` directly.

```ts
// ✅ GOOD — single focused side effect, registered with EventBus
@EventsHandler(OrderPlacedEvent)
@Injectable()
export class OnOrderPlacedHandler implements IEventHandler<OrderPlacedEvent> {
  constructor(private readonly commandBus: CommandBus) {}

  async handle(event: OrderPlacedEvent): Promise<void> {
    // e.g. trigger a downstream command or call an application port
    await this.commandBus.execute(
      new SendOrderConfirmationCommand(event.orderId, event.customerId),
    );
  }
}

// ❌ BAD — mutates domain state inside an event handler
async handle(event: OrderPlacedEvent) {
  event.order.cancel();   // ← mutation belongs in a command handler
}

// ❌ BAD — calls Prisma directly
async handle(event: OrderPlacedEvent) {
  await this.prisma.order.update({ where: { id: event.orderId }, data: { notified: true } });
}
```

