## `ports/` — Application-Level Ports

These interfaces represent cross-cutting concerns that the application layer needs but that are not domain concepts. Implemented in the presentation or infrastructure layer and injected via DI tokens.

| Port | Interface token | Implementation |
|---|---|---|
| `ICurrentUserPort` | `Symbol('ICurrentUserPort')` | `CurrentUserAdapter` from `@lib/core` |
| `IAuthorizationPort` | `Symbol('IAuthorizationPort')` | feature-specific or shared |

**Rules:**
- Pure TypeScript interfaces — no `@Injectable()`, no NestJS types.
- Same token naming rule: `Symbol` name = interface name.
- Implementations live in the **presentation** or **infrastructure** layer, never in the application or domain layer.

### `ICurrentUserPort` — full implementation guide

The port, adapter, and interceptor all ship in `@lib/core`. Feature modules only need to register the binding.

**Port (application layer — defines the contract):**

```ts
// src/core/application/ports/current-user.port.ts
export const ICurrentUserPort = Symbol('ICurrentUserPort');

export interface ICurrentUserPort {
  getUserId(): string;           // stable user identifier (sub claim)
  getEmail(): string | undefined;
  getRoles(): string[];
  getPermissions(): string[];
  hasRole(role: string): boolean;
  hasPermission(permission: string): boolean;
}
```

**How it flows end-to-end:**

```
HTTP request arrives
    │
    ▼
UnifiedAuthGuard               ← sets request.user (AuthUser) — from @lib/auth
    │
    ▼
CommandHandler.execute()
    │  (NestJS injects a fresh CurrentUserAdapter instance for this request)
    ▼
this.currentUser.getUserId()   ← CurrentUserAdapter reads request.user directly
                                  same mechanism as @CurrentUser() decorator
```

**No extra setup needed** — `CurrentUserAdapter` uses `@Inject(REQUEST)` and `Scope.REQUEST`, exactly the same way `@CurrentUser()` reads `request.user`.

**Global registration in `AppModule`:**

```ts
// app.module.ts
// Nothing extra needed globally — just register the binding per module below.
```

**Per-module binding (in each module that needs current user in handlers):**

```ts
// order.module.ts
import { CurrentUserAdapter, ICurrentUserPort } from '@lib/core';

@Module({
  providers: [
    { provide: ICurrentUserPort, useClass: CurrentUserAdapter },
    PlaceOrderHandler,
  ],
})
export class OrderModule {}
```

**Using in a command handler:**

```ts
@CommandHandler(PlaceOrderCommand)
@Injectable()
export class PlaceOrderHandler implements ICommandHandler<PlaceOrderCommand> {
  constructor(
    @Inject(IOrderRepository) private readonly repo: IOrderRepository,
    @Inject(ICurrentUserPort) private readonly currentUser: ICurrentUserPort,
    private readonly eventBus: EventBus,
  ) {}

  async execute(command: PlaceOrderCommand): Promise<OrderResponseDto> {
    const userId = this.currentUser.getUserId();   // ← reads request.user, no HTTP import

    const order = Order.create(command.items, userId);
    await this.repo.save(order);

    this.eventBus.publishAll(order.domainEvents);
    order.clearEvents();
    return OrderResponseMapper.toDto(order);
  }
}
```

**Scope cascade — what it means in practice:**

`CurrentUserAdapter` is `Scope.REQUEST`. NestJS automatically makes any handler that injects it REQUEST-scoped too — a fresh instance per request. For most handlers this is invisible and harmless. If you need to avoid it (e.g. a hot-path handler with expensive construction), pass `userId` through the command instead.

**Pass via command vs inject via port — when to use which:**

| Scenario | Use |
|---|---|
| User identity is part of the business intent (e.g. `cancelledBy`) | Pass in command constructor |
| Handler needs `hasRole()` / `hasPermission()` checks | Inject `ICurrentUserPort` |
| User identity is needed in many nested calls | Inject `ICurrentUserPort` |

